04331nam a22006255i 9780292795037DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927950377 a10.7560/7168892doi  a(DE-B1597)588307  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a529/.329784272221 aRice, Prudence M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaya Calendar Origins :bMonuments, Mythistory, and the Materialization of Time /cPrudence M. Rice. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tNote on Orthography and Dates -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 In the Beginning -- t3 Mesoamerican Calendrics -- t4 Maya Calendar Developments in Broader Context -- t5 Middle and Late Preclassic -- t6 Late Preclassic -- t7 The Early Maya Lowlands -- t8 Early Lowland Maya Intellectual Culture -- t9 The Materialization and Politicization of Time -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Maya Political Science: Time, Astronomy, and the Cosmos, Prudence M. Rice proposed a new model of Maya political organization in which geopolitical seats of power rotated according to a 256-year calendar cycle known as the May. This fundamental connection between timekeeping and Maya political organization sparked Rice's interest in the origins of the two major calendars used by the ancient lowland Maya, one 260 days long, and the other having 365 days. In Maya Calendar Origins, she presents a provocative new thesis about the origins and development of the calendrical system. Integrating data from anthropology, archaeology, art history, astronomy, ethnohistory, myth, and linguistics, Rice argues that the Maya calendars developed about a millennium earlier than commonly thought, around 1200 BC, as an outgrowth of observations of the natural phenomena that scheduled the movements of late Archaic hunter-gatherer-collectors throughout what became Mesoamerica. She asserts that an understanding of the cycles of weather and celestial movements became the basis of power for early rulers, who could thereby claim "control" over supernatural cosmic forces. Rice shows how time became materialized—transformed into status objects such as monuments that encoded calendrical or temporal concerns—as well as politicized, becoming the foundation for societal order, political legitimization, and wealth. Rice's research also sheds new light on the origins of the Popol Vuh, which, Rice believes, encodes the history of the development of the Mesoamerican calendars. She also explores the connections between the Maya and early Olmec and Izapan cultures in the Isthmian region, who shared with the Maya the cosmovision and ideology incorporated into the calendrical systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMaya calendar. 0aMaya chronology. 0aMaya cosmology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71688940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795037423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795037/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK